We have level 20s who have to constantly have KEI nowadays. I honestly don't think they're cut out for any sort of additional challenges the devs might toss their way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 3727<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/31/03 5:02:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Spell A has a level restriction on it. There's a bunch of spells like this. You cannot get it cast on you unless you are level X.<br>
<br>
Unless you're grouped.<br>
<br>
So everyone groups.<br>
<br>
Is that an exploit? Why or why not? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->First, we'd need to know whether or not it is a design intention that being grouped should let you use buffs that you would otherwise not be able to.  Since players don't know the minds of the developer, this would not be an &quot;exploit&quot; in the mind of a player until he can reasonably know otherwise.  Because clearly arguments on both sides can be made:<br>
<br>
1.  Ignoring the level restriction in a group promotes grouping and increases interaction.<br>
2.  The above was not intended, that group buffs land on low level people is a bug, therefore it is an exploit.<br>
<br>
However, this gets less convincing as you consider levels that can not feasibly group together for experience, and only group temporarily to get the benefits of the buff.  KEI would be a good example of what is fairly clearly an unintended design consequence, that is, the extreme duration of the spell.  Even if the above #1 is true, the ability to have 99%+ buff effectiveness while ungrouped would clearly not fit into that argument.  Thus I would say that a level 15 getting KEI is exploiting the removal level restriction in a group.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Edit:  actually, I would generally give the benefit of the doubt to the recipient and blame the buff-caster.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I would also say that this exploit is a fairly mild concern.  It's an exploit, but it's hard to say how serious without seeing some low level data.  It's not something to ban people over but it's something that they should definitely try to fix if they could do so without breaking something else and if they have the opportunity.<br>
